# React 19 Cursor Rules

## Architecture
- Use Server Components by default, Client Components only when needed (interactivity, hooks, browser APIs)
- Prefer function components with hooks over class components
- Co-locate related files: `Component.tsx`, `Component.test.tsx`, `Component.module.css`
- Use barrel exports (`index.ts`) sparingly — they hurt tree-shaking

## Component Patterns
- Name components with PascalCase: `UserProfile`, `NavigationBar`
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks prefixed with `use`: `useAuth`, `useLocalStorage`
- Keep components under 150 lines — split into smaller components if larger
- Use `React.memo()` only when profiling shows re-render issues, not preemptively

## Hooks Rules
- DO: Call hooks at the top level of components
- DON'T: Call hooks inside loops, conditions, or nested functions
- DO: Use `useCallback` for event handlers passed to memoized children
- DON'T: Wrap every function in `useCallback` — it has overhead
- DO: Use `useMemo` for expensive computations
- DON'T: Use `useMemo` for simple values or primitives

## State Management
- Local state: `useState` for simple, `useReducer` for complex
- Shared state: Context for theme/auth, Zustand/Jotai for complex global state
- Server state: TanStack Query for data fetching, caching, and synchronization
- DO: Lift state up only as far as needed
- DON'T: Put everything in global state

## React 19 Features
- Use `use()` hook for reading resources (promises, context)
- Use `useActionState` for form actions with pending states
- Use `useOptimistic` for optimistic UI updates
- Server Actions: Define with `'use server'` directive for mutations

## Performance
- Use `React.lazy()` and `Suspense` for code splitting
- Avoid inline object/array creation in JSX props (causes re-renders)
- Use `key` prop properly — never use array index for dynamic lists
- Prefer CSS for animations over JS-driven re-renders

## Error Handling
- Wrap feature boundaries with `ErrorBoundary` components
- Use `Suspense` boundaries for loading states
- Handle async errors in effects with cleanup functions

## TypeScript Integration
- Define props with interfaces, not types (for better error messages)
- Use `React.FC` sparingly — prefer explicit return types
- Export prop interfaces for reusable components
- Use generics for flexible, type-safe components
